1. Authentication vs Authorization
Authentication
Authentication answers:
Who are you?
It verifies the identity of the user.
Example:
•	Username
•	Password
•	Certificate
•	Token
Example in OpenShift:
oc login -u developer -p developer
The cluster verifies the credentials using an Identity Provider.
________________________________________
Authorization
Authorization answers:
What are you allowed to do?
It determines:
•	which resources
•	which actions
a user can perform.
OpenShift uses RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) for authorization.
Example:
User → allowed to create pods
User → NOT allowed to delete projects
________________________________________
2. OpenShift Security Resources
OpenShift has several resources for authentication and authorization.
________________________________________
User
A User represents a person or system interacting with the cluster.
Example:
developer
admin
student
User objects are created automatically after login.
Example:
oc get users
Example output:
NAME
developer
admin
________________________________________
Identity
An Identity records:
which identity provider authenticated the user
Example identity format:
provider:user
Example:
htpasswd:student
Command:
oc get identities
Example:
htpasswd:student
________________________________________
Service Account
A Service Account is used by applications or pods to access the API.
Why?
Pods should not use real user credentials.
Example:
default
builder
deployer
Command:
oc get sa
Example use:
Pods use service accounts to:
•	read secrets
•	deploy resources
•	communicate with API
________________________________________
Group
A Group is a collection of users.
Instead of assigning roles individually:
User1
User2
User3
You assign roles to a group.
Example:
developers
admins
qa-team
Command:
oc get groups
Example:
developers
Users inside group:
developer1
developer2
developer3
________________________________________
Role
A Role defines permissions inside a project (namespace).
Example permissions:
create pods
read services
update deployments
Roles are project-level.
Example:
view
edit
admin
Command:
oc get roles
________________________________________
ClusterRole
A ClusterRole defines permissions across the entire cluster.
Examples:
cluster-admin
cluster-reader
cluster-monitoring
Command:
oc get clusterroles
ClusterRoles can apply to:
•	all namespaces
•	cluster resources
________________________________________
3. Authentication Process in OpenShift
When a user sends a request:
User → API Server
Process:
1 User sends request
2 Authentication verifies identity
3 Authorization checks RBAC permissions
4 Request allowed or denied
________________________________________
4. Authentication Methods in OpenShift
OpenShift supports two main methods.
________________________________________
1 OAuth Access Token
Most common method.
Example login:
oc login -u developer -p developer
Flow:
User → OAuth Server → Identity Provider → Token issued
Token is then used for API requests.
________________________________________
2 X.509 Client Certificates
Used mainly by cluster administrators.
Certificate stored in:
kubeconfig
Example:
~/.kube/config
________________________________________
5. Anonymous Authentication
If no token or certificate is provided:
User becomes:
system:anonymous
Group:
system:unauthenticated
These users have almost no permissions.
________________________________________
6. OpenShift OAuth Server
OpenShift runs an OAuth Server.
Component:
Authentication Operator
Purpose:
Validate users
Generate access tokens
Integrate identity providers
Process:
User login
     ↓
OAuth server
     ↓
Identity provider validation
     ↓
Token issued
________________________________________
7. Identity Providers
OpenShift supports multiple identity providers.
Common ones:
Provider	Use Case
HTPasswd	simple username/password
LDAP	enterprise directory
GitHub	GitHub login
OpenID	SSO providers
Keystone	OpenStack
Multiple identity providers can be configured.
________________________________________
8. HTPasswd Identity Provider
HTPasswd uses a file containing usernames and hashed passwords.
Example file:
student:$apr1$rnrDU...
admin:$apr1$ksd89...
This file is stored in a secret.
Best used for:
testing
development
lab environments
Not recommended for production.
________________________________________
9. Creating an HTPasswd File
Tool used:
htpasswd
Package:
httpd-tools
________________________________________
Create new htpasswd file
Command:
htpasswd -c -B -b /tmp/htpasswd student redhat123
Explanation:
Option	Meaning
-c	create new file
-B	bcrypt encryption
-b	password in command
Example result:
student:$2y$05$kjsdfkjsdf...
________________________________________
Add another user
htpasswd -B -b /tmp/htpasswd developer pass123
________________________________________
Change password
htpasswd -B -b /tmp/htpasswd student newpass
________________________________________
Delete user
htpasswd -D /tmp/htpasswd student
________________________________________
10. Create HTPasswd Secret
OpenShift requires the htpasswd file stored in a secret.
Command:
oc create secret generic htpasswd-secret \
--from-file htpasswd=/tmp/htpasswd \
-n openshift-config
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
secret generic	create secret
htpasswd-secret	secret name
--from-file	load file
openshift-config	namespace
Important:
htpasswd=filename
is required.
________________________________________
11. Extract Secret Data
If you want to edit users later:
oc extract secret/htpasswd-secret \
-n openshift-config \
--to /tmp/ \
--confirm
This extracts the htpasswd file.
________________________________________
12. Update Secret
After editing the file:
oc set data secret/htpasswd-secret \
--from-file htpasswd=/tmp/htpasswd \
-n openshift-config
Then authentication pods restart automatically.
Check:
watch oc get pods -n openshift-authentication
________________________________________
13. Configure OAuth Identity Provider
You must modify the OAuth cluster configuration.
Export configuration:
oc get oauth cluster -o yaml > oauth.yaml
Edit file.
Example configuration:
apiVersion: config.openshift.io/v1
kind: OAuth
metadata:
  name: cluster
spec:
  identityProviders:
  - name: my_htpasswd_provider
    mappingMethod: claim
    type: HTPasswd
    htpasswd:
      fileData:
        name: htpasswd-secret
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
name	provider name
mappingMethod	identity mapping
type	provider type
fileData	secret name
________________________________________
14. Apply Configuration
Command:
oc replace -f oauth.yaml
Authentication pods restart.
Users can now login.
Example:
oc login -u student -p redhat123
________________________________________
15. Delete Users Completely
Deleting user requires multiple steps.
________________________________________
Step 1 Remove from htpasswd
htpasswd -D /tmp/htpasswd manager
________________________________________
Step 2 Update secret
oc set data secret/htpasswd-secret \
--from-file htpasswd=/tmp/htpasswd \
-n openshift-config
________________________________________
Step 3 Delete user resource
oc delete user manager
________________________________________
Step 4 Delete identity resource
Find identity:
oc get identities
Example:
my_htpasswd_provider:manager
Delete:
oc delete identity my_htpasswd_provider:manager
________________________________________
16. Assign Cluster Admin Role
To give full cluster access:
oc adm policy add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin student
Meaning:
student → full cluster admin
________________________________________
17. Cluster Administrator Authentication
Cluster admins can authenticate in two ways.
________________________________________
Method 1 kubeconfig file
Set environment variable:
export KUBECONFIG=/home/user/auth/kubeconfig
Then run:
oc get nodes
________________________________________
Method 2 kubeadmin user
Login command:
oc login -u kubeadmin -p PASSWORD
Password stored in:
/home/lab/ocp4/auth/kubeadmin-password
________________________________________
18. Delete kubeadmin User
Once real admins are created:
oc delete secret kubeadmin -n kube-system
But never delete before creating another admin.
Otherwise cluster may become inaccessible.
________________________________________
19. Full Workflow Summary
HTPasswd setup workflow:
1 Create htpasswd file
2 Create secret
3 Configure OAuth identity provider
4 Apply configuration
5 Login with new users
6 Assign RBAC roles
________________________________________
